{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is the handoff between request-construction and API-client dispatch; a pure unit test of only the builder can miss dropped/renamed fields during module wiring. No real OS/network/subprocess is required, and correctness does not depend on model judgment. Rejected higher levels: behavior text is payload-shape/orchestration only, not live HTTP behavior or LLM output quality. Adversarial critique: if implementation is literally one pure function that returns final payload used directly, Unit could be sufficient.","test_description":"Wire classifier module to a stub transport that records outbound payload. Invoke classification with a taxonomy of 4+ labels and assert the sent request contains the full taxonomy list (no omissions/reordering-loss from serialization path).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The real failure is response-handoff plus validation (client response -> normalization/validation -> public return). A stubbed API response with an out-of-taxonomy label can expose this without real network or model variability. Rejected higher levels: behavior text focuses on deterministic post-processing of a returned value, not live provider behavior quality. Adversarial critique: if validation is isolated in one pure function and everything else is pass-through, Unit could catch it.","test_description":"Use a fake API client returning `\"nonsense_label\"`; call classify and assert module returns `\"unknown\"` to caller, proving boundary validation is enforced after response ingestion.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.4,"Integration":0.5,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For identical raw API responses, the module's normalization step always produces the same final label.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This behavior is a pure determinism/property check on normalization logic for identical input; no cross-module, infrastructure, or model dependence is required. Rejected higher levels: behavior text explicitly constrains to identical raw responses and normalization output, disqualifying System/Agentic/Workflow needs. Adversarial critique: if normalization reads mutable external state (config/locale/time), then Integration may be needed.","test_description":"Call normalization function/object twice (or property-test many times) with the exact same raw API payload and assert identical final label each time.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.85,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"On repeated live API calls for the same document and taxonomy, the returned label remains consistent unless the provider response itself changes.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior explicitly requires repeated live calls and consistency of model-driven classification. A mock would hide real nondeterminism/provider drift, so real model output is part of correctness. Not Workflow: this is repeated single-step classification calls, not a multi-agentic pipeline with dependent stages. Adversarial critique: if objective were only client-side caching/replay determinism under fixed captured responses, Integration would suffice.","test_description":"Run N repeated calls against the real provider for the same document/taxonomy over a short window; record raw provider responses and final labels; assert label changes only co-occur with raw-response changes.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Request construction enforces the configured token budget before dispatch (for example truncate/reject according to policy).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure appears at module boundary between token-budget enforcement and dispatch gate (truncate/reject path must control whether and how request is sent). Can be caught with in-process wiring plus stub client; no real HTTP/OS needed. Rejected higher levels: text says enforcement occurs before dispatch, so live provider/model behavior is not required. Adversarial critique: if budget enforcement is a single pure function returning transformed text with no dispatch coupling, Unit may be enough.","test_description":"Configure low token budget; invoke classify with oversized document; verify policy outcome (truncate or reject) and assert dispatch behavior matches policy (modified payload sent or no call made).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.58,"System":0.09,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This depends on real external API metering/reporting. In-process fakes cannot reveal mismatches between local assumptions and provider-reported usage. Not Agentic: assertion is on token accounting, not semantic quality/decision correctness of model output. Rejected higher levels: no multi-step agentic chain. Adversarial critique: if code only compares a local tokenizer estimate against budget (without trusting provider reports), Integration could suffice.","test_description":"Execute real API call(s) with representative document and capture provider-reported token usage fields; assert usage <= configured budget for the selected model/settings.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.78,"Agentic":0.12,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Core failure boundary is retry orchestration across modules (error interpretation, backoff policy, retry loop). A stub client plus fake clock can expose real logic failures without real network. Integration brake checks: no required OS/subprocess behavior, no dependence on model output quality, and no multi-agentic chain. Rejected higher levels: behavior text is infrastructure handling around API errors, not live LLM decision quality. Adversarial critique: if production bug depends on real HTTP semantics (e.g., exact Retry-After parsing/transport behavior), System may be required.","test_description":"Stub API to return rate-limit signal on first call and success on second; use controllable clock/sleeper; assert module waits per policy, retries, and returns successful label instead of surfacing initial error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.57,"System":0.23,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}}]}
